      { "scenario": "External API returns HTTP 200 but with malformed or empty payload", "handling": "unhandled", "recommendation": "Validate response schema before processing. Add a sanity check: if item count drops by >90% from last known count, log a warning and optionally skip the write to prevent zeroing out stock." },
      { "scenario": "Database write fails mid-sync", "handling": "unhandled", "recommendation": "Wrap the DB write in a transaction. On failure, roll back the entire batch and log the failure with item count context. Do not leave the database in a partially-updated state." },
      { "scenario": "Overlapping sync runs due to previous run not completing within 5 minutes", "handling": "unhandled", "recommendation": "Add a mutex or leader-lock mechanism. If a sync is already in progress when the next interval fires, skip the run and log a warning. This is critical evidence that the timeout or API latency needs attention." },
      { "scenario": "Service process crashes or is OOM-killed", "handling": "partial", "recommendation": "Container orchestrator will restart the process, but there is no health check for the orchestrator to use. Add a /health endpoint that reports last successful sync time so liveness/readiness probes can detect a zombie process." }
    ],
    "retry_config": "None. Every API failure is silently dropped until the next 5-minute interval. A 5-minute retry window is far too coarse — transient network blips lasting <1 second will cause a full 5-minute gap in sync freshness.",
    "timeout_config": "None. The outbound HTTP call has no timeout. This is a production-critical deficiency — a single hung connection can disable the sync service indefinitely.",
    "circuit_breakers": "None. If the external API is persistently down, the service will hammer it every 5 minutes forever with no backoff, no alerting threshold, and no self-protective behavior.",
    "graceful_degradation": "None. There is no concept of 'stale data is acceptable for N minutes' vs 'stale data is a critical incident'. The service has no way to signal to consumers that stock counts may be outdated."
